  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_203_clausal_reduction",
  "title": "C1.203 Clausal Reduction — Economy of Expression",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we often shorten complex sentences: 'After I finished, I left' becomes 'After finishing, I left.' Spanish does this too through **clausal reduction**—turning full subordinate clauses into shorter structures with infinitives or gerunds. *Después de terminar, me fui.* Both languages compress meaning by dropping subjects and auxiliary verbs. English uses the '-ing' form to sound natural; Spanish uses infinitives and participles to sound elegant. English simplifies with rhythm; Spanish simplifies with grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The concept:**\nA **reduced clause** condenses a full dependent clause into a simpler phrase—keeping meaning but removing redundant words. Spanish favors this in writing and fluent speech.\n\nFull clause → *Después de que terminé el trabajo, me fui.*  \nReduced clause → *Después de terminar el trabajo, me fui.*\n\n**2️⃣ Main methods of reduction:**\n| Type | Original clause | Reduced form | Function |\n|------|------------------|---------------|-----------|\n| Infinitive phrase | *Antes de que empieces, avísame.* | *Antes de empezar, avísame.* | Time reference, same subject |\n| Gerund phrase | *Como estaba cansado, se fue a dormir.* | *Estando cansado, se fue a dormir.* | Cause or condition |\n| Past participle | *Una vez que fue terminado, se publicó.* | *Terminado, se publicó.* | Completed action |\n\n**3️⃣ Subject agreement rule:**\nIf both clauses share the same subject → **infinitive or gerund** may replace the subordinate clause.  \nIf subjects differ → **keep the full clause** with *que* + conjugated verb.\n- *Después de estudiar, fui al cine.* (Same subject → reduced.)\n- *Después de que él estudió, fui al cine.* (Different subject → full clause.)\n\n**4️⃣ Prepositions used in reduction:**\n| Preposition | Example | Meaning |\n|--------------|----------|----------|\n| antes de + infinitive | *Antes de salir, apaga la luz.* | before doing |\n| después de + infinitive | *Después de comer, dormimos.* | after doing |\n| al + infinitive | *Al llegar, te llamo.* | upon doing |\n| sin + infinitive | *Salió sin decir nada.* | without doing |\n| con + infinitive / gerund | *Conociendo la verdad, actuó distinto.* | knowing / given that |\n\n**5️⃣ Stylistic benefit:**\nClausal reduction keeps Spanish fluid and formal, avoiding repetition. It’s a hallmark of advanced writing where brevity equals sophistication."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Derived from Latin’s non-finite verbal forms, Spanish inherited reduction as a stylistic device—allowing subordinate ideas to flow without full repetition.",
      "story": "Clausal reduction is Spanish efficiency at its finest—grace built into grammar. It allows ideas to breathe without clutter, trusting the listener to fill in what’s missing. A phrase like *Al llegar, te llamo* carries the same meaning as an entire clause but sounds effortless, almost musical.\n\nThis structure reflects how Spanish handles thought: layered but fluid. Rather than dividing ideas into strict logic, it weaves them together through rhythm. Reduced clauses show confidence in understanding—speakers assume shared context. *Sin decir palabra, salió.* (Without saying a word, he left.) The silence inside the phrase feels deliberate, poetic. Spanish reduction balances sound and sense, trimming grammar without cutting meaning.\n\nWriters and speakers use this form to create intimacy and elegance. It keeps attention on the action, not the structure. *Antes de amanecer, partieron.* The simplicity hides mastery. Every reduced clause suggests motion—language moving forward without hesitation.",
      "wrap_line": "Spanish reduction transforms structure into flow—grammar that saves words but not meaning, turning complexity into calm clarity."
    },
