{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_206_mood_shifts_in_narrative",
  "title": "C1.206 Mood Shifts in Narrative — Grammar of Distance",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English storytelling, we often shift tone or tense to separate action from reflection: 'He was running when he realized he might not make it.' Spanish achieves the same effect through **mood shifts**—moving between the **indicative** for what’s seen and the **subjunctive** for what’s felt or imagined. *Corría cuando pensó que no fuera posible.* English distinguishes fact and thought by perspective; Spanish distinguishes them by **mood**, giving narration emotional and psychological depth inside its grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Purpose:**\nNarrative mood shifts help Spanish weave **perception, emotion, and uncertainty** into storytelling. While the indicative reports what happened, the subjunctive enters the character’s inner world—doubt, fear, memory, or imagination.\n\n**2️⃣ When shifts appear:**\n| Situation | Mood Used | Example |\n|------------|------------|----------|\n| Main action / facts | Indicative | *El hombre llegó tarde.* (The man arrived late.) |\n| Thoughts or unreal possibilities | Subjunctive | *Pensó que no fuera posible llegar a tiempo.* (He thought it might not be possible to arrive on time.) |\n| Reported doubt / hearsay | Subjunctive | *Creían que estuviera enfermo.* (They believed he might be sick.) |\n| Scene-setting or memory | Imperfect subjunctive | *Buscaba algo que lo salvara.* (He was looking for something that could save him.) |\n| Emotional evaluation | Subjunctive | *Era triste que no lo entendieran.* (It was sad they didn’t understand.) |\n\n**3️⃣ Key pattern — The interior turn:**\nWhen narration shifts from the **external** to the **internal**, verbs often slide into the subjunctive.  \n- *Sabía que su padre estaba allí.* → external, real.  \n- *Deseaba que su padre estuviera allí.* → internal, emotional.\n\n**4️⃣ Narrative effects:**\n- **Temporal layering:** The subjunctive places the reader inside thought rather than sequence.  \n- **Emotional focus:** The change of mood invites empathy.  \n- **Stylistic variation:** The interplay between moods creates rhythm—fact alternating with reflection.\n\n**5️⃣ Mood cues:**\nLook for verbs of thought (*creer, imaginar, suponer*), emotion (*temer, alegrarse, lamentar*), and perception (*parecer, sentir, notar*). These often trigger subjunctive structures when the speaker doesn’t claim certainty.\n\n**6️⃣ Quick guide:**\n- Indicative → world as observed.  \n- Subjunctive → world as felt.  \nSpanish uses grammar not only to tell the story, but to **inhabit** it."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s dual mood system, Spanish retained the subjunctive’s power to blend external narration with internal consciousness, giving modern prose a distinct psychological texture.",
