  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_207_complex_conditionals",
  "title": "C1.207 Complex Conditionals — Layers of Hypothesis",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'if' to imagine different kinds of reality: 'If it rains, we’ll stay home' (real), 'If I won the lottery, I’d travel' (unreal), 'If I had known, I’d have gone' (impossible past). Spanish mirrors these same ideas with **complex conditionals** built from *si* clauses, but shifts between **indicative, subjunctive, and conditional** to show the degree of imagination. English uses tense to express likelihood; Spanish uses **mood and sequence**, building logic through harmony rather than time."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The three foundations:**\nSpanish conditionals form clear hierarchies of reality.\n\n| Type | Structure | Example | Meaning |\n|------|------------|----------|----------|\n| 1 — Real / Likely | *Si + present indicative → future or present* | *Si llueve, me quedo en casa.* (If it rains, I stay home.) | A real condition, possible result. |\n| 2 — Unreal / Hypothetical | *Si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional simple* | *Si tuviera dinero, viajaría.* (If I had money, I would travel.) | Imagined or unlikely situation. |\n| 3 — Impossible / Regret | *Si + pluperfect subjunctive → conditional perfect* | *Si hubiera estudiado, habría aprobado.* (If I had studied, I would have passed.) | Unreal past condition. |\n\n**2️⃣ Complex (mixed) conditionals:**\nSpanish allows time to cross between the 'if' clause and the result clause. This creates layered meaning:\n\n| Structure | Example | Meaning |\n|------------|----------|----------|\n| *Si hubiera estudiado, tendría un buen trabajo.* | If I had studied, I’d have a good job. | Past condition → present result. |\n| *Si fuera más valiente, habría confesado la verdad.* | If I were braver, I would have confessed the truth. | Present condition → past result. |\n\n**3️⃣ Variations in tone:**\n- *Si acaso* (just in case): *Llama si acaso no llego a tiempo.*  \n- *Como si* (as if): *Habla como si lo supiera todo.*  \n- *A menos que* (unless): *No saldré a menos que termines.*\n\n**4️⃣ Sequence of moods:**\n| Clause 1 | Clause 2 | Meaning |\n|-----------|-----------|----------|\n| Present indicative | Future / Present | Real, factual outcome |\n| Imperfect subjunctive | Conditional simple | Imagined present or future |\n| Pluperfect subjunctive | Conditional perfect | Regretful past |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nSpanish keeps tense harmony not just for time, but for emotional coherence. Every pair of verbs balances belief, doubt, and distance from reality."
