  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_208_concessive_phrases",
  "title": "C1.208 Concessive Phrases — Grammar of Balance",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use phrases like 'even if,' 'no matter how,' or 'though' to show contrast that doesn’t stop the main idea: 'Even if it rains, I’ll go,' 'No matter what happens, I’ll try.' Spanish expresses this balance between resistance and persistence through **concessive phrases**—*aunque, por más que, a pesar de que, incluso si.* English uses tone to show determination; Spanish uses structure to let grammar bend but not break under contradiction."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What concessive phrases do:**\nThey acknowledge an obstacle while affirming that the main idea still holds. In Spanish, the key connectors are:\n\n| Connector | Meaning | Mood | Example |\n|------------|----------|------|----------|\n| *aunque* | although / even if | indicative (fact) or subjunctive (possibility) | *Aunque llueva, saldré.* (Even if it rains, I’ll go.) |\n| *por más que / por mucho que* | no matter how much | subjunctive | *Por más que lo intente, no podré olvidarte.* (No matter how hard I try, I won’t forget you.) |\n| *a pesar de que* | despite / even though | indicative / subjunctive | *A pesar de que estaba cansado, siguió trabajando.* |\n| *incluso si* | even if | indicative / subjunctive | *Incluso si gritas, no te oirán.* |\n\n**2️⃣ Indicative vs. subjunctive distinction:**\n- **Indicative** = the obstacle is real or known.\n  - *Aunque está enfermo, vino a trabajar.* (Although he’s sick, he came to work.)\n- **Subjunctive** = the obstacle is hypothetical or uncertain.\n  - *Aunque esté enfermo, vendrá.* (Even if he’s sick, he’ll come.)\n\n**3️⃣ Advanced forms:**\n| Expression | Use | Example |\n|-------------|------|----------|\n| *por mucho que + subjunctive* | emotional emphasis | *Por mucho que supliques, no volveré.* |\n| *sea como sea* | set phrase ('be that as it may') | *Sea como sea, debemos continuar.* |\n| *aun cuando + subjunctive* | formal / literary | *Aun cuando parezca difícil, lo lograremos.* |\n\n**4️⃣ Placement and tone:**\nThese phrases can open or interrupt a sentence, depending on emphasis:  \n- *A pesar de todo, lo hizo.* / *Lo hizo, a pesar de todo.*\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen English uses 'even if' or 'no matter what,' Spanish nearly always calls for the **subjunctive.** When it uses 'although' for a real situation, choose the **indicative.** Spanish measures defiance through mood, not volume."
