  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use expressions that can’t be taken literally: 'It’s raining cats and dogs,' 'Break a leg,' 'I’m under the weather.' Spanish has its own **idiomatic structures**, where words combine to express something beyond logic. *Estar en las nubes* (to be daydreaming), *dar en el clavo* (to hit the nail on the head), *no tener pelos en la lengua* (to speak frankly). English builds idioms through imagery; Spanish builds them through rhythm and cultural wit—grammar turned into storytelling."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What idiomatic structures are:**\nAn **idiomatic structure** is a fixed phrase whose meaning cannot be deduced from the literal words. Spanish idioms often rely on verbs, prepositions, and reflexive forms arranged in familiar patterns.\n\n**2️⃣ Common structural types:**\n| Pattern | Example | Literal meaning | Real meaning |\n|----------|----------|-----------------|----------------|\n| *Estar + en + noun* | *Estar en las nubes* | To be in the clouds | To be distracted / daydreaming |\n| *Dar + en + noun* | *Dar en el clavo* | To hit on the nail | To be exactly right |\n| *Tener + noun + en + noun* | *Tener la cabeza en otro lado* | To have your head elsewhere | To be absent-minded |\n| *No tener + noun + en + noun* | *No tener pelos en la lengua* | To have no hairs on the tongue | To speak openly |\n| *Ir(se) + por + noun* | *Irse por las ramas* | To go through the branches | To beat around the bush |\n\n**3️⃣ Grammatical notes:**\n- Verb conjugation still follows normal tense and person: *Estoy en las nubes, estaba en las nubes, estaré en las nubes.*\n- Some idioms require pronouns (*irse, meterse, darse cuenta de*).  \n- Articles and prepositions rarely change, even if logic suggests they should. Idioms freeze structure but allow movement through conjugation.\n\n**4️⃣ Categories of idiomatic meaning:**\n| Theme | Example | Translation |\n|--------|----------|--------------|\n| Emotion | *Estar hasta las narices (de algo)* | To be fed up with something |\n| Success / failure | *Dar en el clavo / meter la pata* | To get it right / to mess up |\n| Honesty | *Decir las cosas como son* | To tell things as they are |\n| Luck / chance | *Tener suerte / estar de suerte* | To be lucky |\n| Behavior | *Hacer la vista gorda* | To turn a blind eye |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nIdioms in Spanish are grammatically predictable but semantically surprising. Once you learn the structure, you can spot meaning by pattern, not translation."
