    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The foundation:**\nSpanish uses **registers of speech** to balance respect and familiarity. The choice between *tú, usted, vosotros, ustedes* defines social distance and tone.\n\n| Pronoun | Use | Example | Translation |\n|----------|------|----------|-------------|\n| tú | informal, singular | *¿Cómo estás?* | How are you? (to a friend) |\n| usted | formal, singular | *¿Cómo está?* | How are you? (to an elder or stranger) |\n| vosotros | informal, plural (Spain) | *¿Cómo estáis?* | How are you all? |\n| ustedes | formal plural (Spain) / general plural (Latin America) | *¿Cómo están?* | How are you (all)? |\n\n**2️⃣ Verb agreement:**\nEach pronoun changes not just tone, but **verb conjugation**.\n- *Tú hablas* → friendly / direct.  \n- *Usted habla* → polite / distant.  \n- *Vosotros habláis* → informal group (Spain only).  \n- *Ustedes hablan* → plural everywhere; formal in Spain, neutral elsewhere.\n\n**3️⃣ Registers through vocabulary:**\nSpanish formality is reinforced through choice of words:\n| Formal | Neutral | Informal |\n|---------|----------|----------|\n| *buenos días* | *hola* | *¿qué tal?* |\n| *disculpe* | *perdón* | *oye* |\n| *quisiera / podría* | *quiero / puedo* | *dame / hazme* |\n\n**4️⃣ Regional variation:**\nIn Latin America, *usted* can sound warm rather than distant—especially in Colombia or Costa Rica. In Spain, *tú* is widely accepted even in semi-formal contexts, while *usted* may feel stiff or ironic.\n\n**5️⃣ Beyond pronouns:**\nRegister also appears in verb mood. The **subjunctive** often signals deference or tact:\n- *Quisiera hablar con usted.* (I would like to speak with you.)\n- *Si me permite, le explico.* (If you’ll allow me, I’ll explain.)\n\n**6️⃣ Quick tip:**\nIn Spanish, relationships are grammatical. The way you conjugate is as revealing as the words you choose."
