    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The function:**\nThe **stylistic subjunctive** transcends normal grammar rules of doubt or desire. It appears in fixed or elevated expressions to add tone—solemnity, artistry, or courtesy.\n\n**2️⃣ Common stylistic forms:**\n| Type | Structure | Example | Meaning |\n|------|------------|----------|----------|\n| Wishes / Blessings | *Que + subjunctive* | *Que tengas suerte.* | May you have luck. |\n| Commands of hope | *Viva + noun* | *¡Viva la libertad!* | Long live freedom. |\n| Concessive phrases | *Sea como sea* | *Be that as it may.* | Acceptance despite uncertainty. |\n| Moral reflection | *Haya paz entre nosotros.* | Let there be peace among us. | Aspiration / formality. |\n| Impersonal tone | *Así sea.* | So be it. | Finality / agreement. |\n\n**3️⃣ Sentence position and intonation:**\nThese expressions often omit subjects and appear standalone—intonation carries emotion rather than structure.\n- *¡Viva el arte!* (spoken with pride)\n- *Que te vaya bien.* (spoken softly, affectionately)\n- *Sea como fuere.* (spoken philosophically)\n\n**4️⃣ Morphological range:**\nThe stylistic subjunctive uses mostly the **present** and **imperfect** forms:\n| Mood | Form | Example |\n|-------|-------|----------|\n| Present Subjunctive | *Viva / tenga / sea* | *Viva España.* |\n| Imperfect Subjunctive | *fuera / tuviera / dijera* | *Fuera lo que fuera, lo amaba.* |\n\n**5️⃣ Exceptions and fixed formulas:**\nSome set phrases use older forms preserved from literary Spanish, such as *amén*, *hágase tu voluntad*, or *bástame saberlo*. They reflect how the subjunctive once carried sacred or ceremonial power.\n\n**6️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen the subjunctive sounds like a wish, blessing, or farewell, it’s functioning stylistically—not logically. Spanish uses mood to give language dignity."
