  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_212_colloquial_imperatives",
  "title": "C1.212 Colloquial Imperatives — Grammar of Tone and Context",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, imperatives change tone with voice: 'Sit down!' sounds strict, but 'Come on, sit down' sounds friendly. Spanish does this through grammar itself. The **colloquial imperative**—forms like *anda*, *venga*, *oye*, *mira*, *vamos*—turns commands into conversation. English adjusts with intonation; Spanish uses fixed imperative phrases to express warmth, disbelief, encouragement, or irony. English relies on delivery; Spanish codes tone directly into the words."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The core idea:**\nColloquial imperatives in Spanish are **fossilized commands**—verbs that no longer function literally but signal tone, attitude, or rhythm in conversation. They show engagement rather than instruction.\n\n**2️⃣ Common forms and uses:**\n| Expression | Literal meaning | Common use / tone |\n|-------------|-----------------|--------------------|\n| *anda* | walk / go on | disbelief, surprise, mild irony (*¡Anda, no me digas!* – Really? No way!) |\n| *venga* | come | encouragement, agreement, finality (*Venga, vámonos.* – Come on, let’s go.) |\n| *oye / oiga* | listen / hey | calling attention (*Oye, te cuento algo.* – Hey, let me tell you something.) |\n| *mira / mire* | look | emphasis or soft introduction (*Mira, no es tan grave.* – Look, it’s not that bad.) |\n| *vamos* | let’s go | encouragement or resignation (*Vamos, inténtalo.* – Come on, try it.) |\n| *hala / vale* | (interjections) | surprise or agreement (*¡Hala, qué rápido!* / *Vale, de acuerdo.*) |\n\n**3️⃣ Politeness and register:**\nSome forms use *tú*; others adapt to *usted* for respect:\n- *Oye* (tú) → *Oiga* (usted)\n- *Mira* (tú) → *Mire* (usted)\n\nThese shifts preserve tone while adjusting social level. The verb changes form, but not function—it still signals connection, not command.\n\n**4️⃣ Function in conversation:**\n- To **soften advice:** *Mira, deberías descansar.* (Look, you should rest.)\n- To **invite empathy:** *Anda, cuéntame más.* (Come on, tell me more.)\n- To **wrap up politely:** *Venga, nos vemos mañana.* (Alright then, see you tomorrow.)\n\n**5️⃣ Quick grammar note:**\nThough these are imperatives, they often occur at the **start or end** of sentences, framing speech with friendliness or persuasion rather than order. Their literal meaning fades; tone becomes everything."
