  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_213_passive_vs_active_subjunctive",
  "title": "C1.213 Passive vs. Active Subjunctive — Grammar of Intention",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we distinguish between active and passive with helper verbs: 'They built the bridge' vs. 'The bridge was built.' Spanish does the same but adds a deeper layer when the **subjunctive mood** enters. *Quiero que construyan el puente* (I want them to build the bridge) shows intention; *Quiero que sea construido* (I want it to be built) shows distance or formality. English changes meaning by switching subjects; Spanish does it by shaping **who acts** and **how much control** the speaker claims."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Core contrast:**\nBoth forms express the same event, but differ in focus and tone.\n| Structure | Meaning | Example |\n|------------|----------|----------|\n| Active subjunctive | Focus on the actor (who does it) | *Quiero que ellos construyan la casa.* (I want them to build the house.) |\n| Passive subjunctive | Focus on the result (what gets done) | *Quiero que la casa sea construida.* (I want the house to be built.) |\n\n**2️⃣ Mechanics of formation:**\nPassive subjunctive = *ser + past participle* (agreeing in gender and number) inside a subjunctive clause.\n- *Espero que el informe sea revisado a tiempo.*\n- *Deseamos que las calles sean reparadas.*\n\n**3️⃣ Agreement rules:**\nThe past participle must match the subject of the sentence:\n| Subject | Verb + participle | Example |\n|----------|-------------------|----------|\n| el libro | *sea leído* | *Esperamos que el libro sea leído pronto.* |\n| las cartas | *sean enviadas* | *Quiero que las cartas sean enviadas hoy.* |\n| la ciudad | *sea reconstruida* | *Desean que la ciudad sea reconstruida.* |\n\n**4️⃣ Register and tone:**\n- **Active subjunctive** feels **personal and direct**—typical in everyday speech.\n  - *Espero que tú hagas el trabajo.* (I hope you do the work.)\n- **Passive subjunctive** feels **formal, objective, or bureaucratic**—common in writing or institutions.\n  - *Se solicita que el trabajo sea entregado mañana.* (It is requested that the work be submitted tomorrow.)\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen the **doer** matters → active. When the **action or outcome** matters → passive. Spanish lets the speaker control emotional distance through grammar rather than tone."
