      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The concept:**\nSpanish verbs control whether a preposition appears. Some verbs inherently include direction or relation in their meaning—making extra prepositions unnecessary. Others require them to clarify who or what is affected.\n\n**2️⃣ Verbs that drop prepositions (direct connection):**\n| English | Spanish | Example |\n|----------|----------|----------|\n| look for | buscar | *Busco mis llaves.* (I’m looking for my keys.) |\n| ask for | pedir | *Pedí ayuda.* (I asked for help.) |\n| wait for | esperar | *Esperamos el tren.* (We’re waiting for the train.) |\n| listen to | escuchar | *Escucho música.* (I listen to music.) |\n| pay for | pagar | *Pagó la cena.* (He paid for dinner.) |\n| enter / leave | entrar / salir | *Entró la casa.* / *Salió la oficina.* |\n\n**3️⃣ Verbs that require prepositions:**\n| Verb | Preposition | Example |\n|------|--------------|----------|\n| depender | de | *Dependo de ti.* (I depend on you.) |\n| pensar | en | *Pienso en ella.* (I think about her.) |\n| soñar | con | *Soñé con mi abuela.* (I dreamed about my grandmother.) |\n| confiar | en | *Confío en mis amigos.* (I trust my friends.) |\n| insistir | en | *Insistió en pagar.* (He insisted on paying.) |\n\n**4️⃣ Rule of motion:**\nWhen verbs of direction or contact imply the relationship themselves, Spanish **omits** the preposition. *Entrar* already implies “into,” *esperar* already implies “for.” The economy comes from precision: why repeat what the verb already says?\n\n**5️⃣ Regional and stylistic notes:**\nIn some dialects (especially Mexico and the Caribbean), speakers may reintroduce prepositions for emphasis (*entrar en la casa*), but educated written Spanish favors omission for clarity and rhythm.\n\n**6️⃣ Quick tip:**\nIf the English verb needs a preposition to sound right, check if the Spanish equivalent already carries that meaning internally. Spanish verbs often do the heavy lifting themselves."
