      "line": "**1️⃣ What emphatic structures do:**\nThey bring attention to part of the sentence—who did it, what was done, or how it felt. Spanish shifts focus by **reordering**, **duplicating pronouns**, or **adding clarifying particles**.\n\n**2️⃣ Main emphatic patterns:**\n| Type | Structure | Example | Meaning |\n|------|------------|----------|----------|\n| Cleft sentence (focus on subject/object) | *Fue + noun/pronoun + quien/lo que + verb* | *Fue Ana quien llamó.* | It was Ana who called. |\n| Focus with *lo que* | *Lo que + clause + es + phrase* | *Lo que necesito es tiempo.* | What I need is time. |\n| Affirmation with *sí* | *Sí + verb* | *Sí vino.* | He *did* come. |\n| Redundancy for focus | *A mí me gusta / A ti te digo.* | *A mí me encanta el café.* | Emphasizes contrast or certainty. |\n| Emotional intensifier | *Que + clause!* | *¡Que no te enteras!* | You just don’t get it! (informal emphasis) |\n\n**3️⃣ Agreement and usage:**\n- *Fue + quien/lo que* agrees with number and gender indirectly through context, not verb form.  \n- Double marking (pronoun + noun) adds insistence: *A ella la vi, no a ti.* (Her—I saw, not you.)\n- *Sí + verb* stresses correction: *Sí tengo dinero* (I do have money), often contrasting earlier denial.\n\n**4️⃣ Intonation and rhythm:**\nWhile English relies on stress, Spanish keeps tone even and lets syntax carry intensity. Pauses around *fue*, *lo que*, or *sí* create clarity and emphasis naturally.\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nSpanish doesn’t italicize or shout; it rearranges. If you want to highlight something, move it to the front or echo it through pronouns. Grammar becomes spotlight—focused, not loud."
