    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What fronting does:**\nFronting is the act of bringing part of a sentence to the beginning to emphasize it. Spanish maintains flexibility thanks to its verb conjugations, which clearly identify the subject—allowing the speaker to move words without losing meaning.\n\n| Standard Order | Fronted Version | Meaning / Focus |\n|----------------|----------------|-----------------|\n| *No me gusta eso.* | *Eso no me gusta.* | Emphasizes 'that' (contrast). |\n| *Vi a María ayer.* | *A María la vi ayer.* | Focus on 'María' (specific person). |\n| *Estoy cansado, la verdad.* | *La verdad, estoy cansado.* | Adds tone of confession or reflection. |\n\n**2️⃣ Common framing structures:**\n| Expression | Function | Example |\n|-------------|-----------|----------|\n| *En cuanto a…* | topic shift / introduction | *En cuanto a tu pregunta, no lo sé.* |\n| *Por mi parte…* | contrastive stance | *Por mi parte, prefiero esperar.* |\n| *Ahora bien…* | formal transition | *Ahora bien, hay que analizarlo.* |\n| *En realidad…* | correction / nuance | *En realidad, no fue así.* |\n\n**3️⃣ Redundant pronouns reinforce focus:**\nWhen an object or person is fronted, the corresponding pronoun often stays in the sentence for grammatical clarity and rhythm.\n- *A Juan lo vi ayer.* (Juan I saw yesterday.)\n- *A mí me dijeron la verdad.* (They told me the truth.)\n\n**4️⃣ Rhythm and tone:**\nFronting doesn’t change grammar—it changes perception. A fronted word signals either contrast (*Eso no me gusta*), affection (*A ti te quiero*), or closure (*Por ahora, basta*). Spanish prefers movement over volume; emphasis flows from order, not stress.\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nIf you want to sound natural, front what matters emotionally or logically. Spanish sentences breathe through rhythm, not punctuation."
