{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C1_218_nominalization",
  "title": "C1.218 Nominalization — Turning Actions into Ideas",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we often turn verbs into nouns: 'Running is fun,' 'Her refusal surprised me,' 'The destruction was massive.' Spanish does this too, but with a wider range of tools. It transforms verbs, adjectives, and even full clauses into **nouns**—ideas that can act as subjects or objects. *El correr es saludable, su negativa me sorprendió, la destrucción fue enorme.* English creates abstract nouns with endings like -ing or -tion; Spanish does it with endings like **-ción, -miento, -dad, -eza, -ura**—grammar that makes thought solid."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The concept:**\nNominalization is the act of turning an action or quality into a **thing**—a noun. Spanish uses this constantly in formal writing, argumentation, and literature to compress ideas and add weight.\n\n**2️⃣ Common nominalizing endings:**\n| Ending | Origin | Example | Meaning |\n|---------|---------|----------|----------|\n| -ción | from Latin -tio | *educación, destrucción* | the act of… (education, destruction) |\n| -miento | from -mentum | *conocimiento, movimiento* | the process/result of… (knowledge, movement) |\n| -dad / -tad | from -tatem | *libertad, amistad* | abstract quality (freedom, friendship) |\n| -eza / -ura | from -itia / -tura | *belleza, dulzura* | quality/state (beauty, sweetness) |\n| -aje | from -aticum | *viaje, paisaje* | collective or action (trip, landscape) |\n\n**3️⃣ Verbal nominalization:**\nYou can also use the **infinitive** as a noun:\n- *El fumar perjudica la salud.* (Smoking harms health.)\n- *El amar es vivir.* (To love is to live.)\n\n**4️⃣ Adjective and clause nominalization:**\nAdjectives and even entire ideas can become nouns when preceded by an article:\n- *Los ricos deben pagar más impuestos.* (The rich should pay more taxes.)\n- *Lo importante es intentarlo.* (The important thing is to try.)\n\n**5️⃣ Formal vs. informal usage:**\n- In formal contexts, nominalization allows conciseness: *La aplicación del método dio buenos resultados.*\n- In everyday speech, too many nominal forms can sound heavy. Balance is key.\n\n**6️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen an English sentence uses *-ing*, *-tion*, or *-ness*, Spanish likely uses **-ción**, **-miento**, or **-dad**—or turns the verb itself into a noun with *el + infinitive.*"
