  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, verbs usually point outward: 'I see you,' 'You hurt me.' Spanish can turn these same actions inward with **pronominal verbs**—forms that use *se, me, te, nos* to show reflection or inner movement. *Me pierdo, se fue, nos miramos.* In poetry, this structure deepens emotion: the action folds back toward the self. English expresses introspection through words; Spanish builds it into grammar—using reflexive verbs to turn language into mirror."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What pronominal verbs are:**\nA **pronominal verb** is a verb used with reflexive pronouns (*me, te, se, nos, os, se*) to show that the subject acts upon itself, or that the action’s focus lies within the subject’s experience.\n\n| Type | Example | Translation | Function |\n|------|----------|--------------|-----------|\n| Reflexive (true self-action) | *Me lavo las manos.* | I wash my hands. | Literal reflection. |\n| Emotional / experiential | *Me pierdo en tus ojos.* | I lose myself in your eyes. | Inner or poetic focus. |\n| Reciprocal (shared) | *Nos miramos.* | We look at each other. | Mutual action. |\n| Idiomatic / pronominal-only | *Quejarse, arrepentirse, suicidarse.* | to complain, repent, commit suicide | Lexically fixed. |\n| Passive / impersonal *se* | *Se vive bien aquí.* | One lives well here. | General or detached action. |\n\n**2️⃣ Mechanics of placement:**\n- Reflexive pronouns appear **before** conjugated verbs: *me levanto, se va.*\n- When attached to infinitives or gerunds, they merge: *voy a acostarme, está vistiéndose.*\n\n**3️⃣ In poetic or emotional language:**\nThe pronoun magnifies inner meaning. Compare:\n- *Perdí el camino.* (I lost the way.) → external fact.\n- *Me perdí en el camino.* (I lost myself on the way.) → spiritual confession.\n\n**4️⃣ Shifts in meaning:**\nMany verbs gain new emotional depth when pronominal:\n| Non-pronominal | Pronominal | Meaning shift |\n|----------------|-------------|----------------|\n| *ir* → to go | *irse* → to leave / depart (emotionally final) |\n| *acordar* → to agree | *acordarse (de)* → to remember |\n| *quedar* → to remain / to meet | *quedarse* → to stay / to be left behind |\n| *volver* → to return | *volverse* → to become (transformation) |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen emotion, identity, or fate enters the sentence, Spanish often turns the verb pronominal. Poetry lives in that transformation."
